that a black hole can be

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:43.250
considered as a similar object.

00:00:43.250 --> 00:00:47.911
And that, actually, black
holes obey the standard law

00:00:47.911 --> 00:00:48.660
of thermodynamics.

00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:59.260
And now we also mentioned
that it's a natural question

00:00:59.260 --> 00:01:02.530
to ask whether the
black hole should we

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:06.200
be considered as an ordinary
quantum mechanical object.

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:09.020
And so this is related to the
issue of information paradox.

00:01:11.680 --> 00:01:15.790
So by this regard, this
information paradox,

00:01:15.790 --> 00:01:21.560
which I think now has a
very good-- in principle

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:25.950
has a reasonable resolution,
which we will talk about later.

00:01:25.950 --> 00:01:29.770
But if we do treat the black
hole as an ordinary quantum

00:01:29.770 --> 00:01:36.080
mechanical object,
then they actually

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:38.055
are very important implications.

00:01:42.920 --> 00:01:47.115
So one implication is called
the holographic principle.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.290
So, the holographic principle
by itself is, in some sense,

00:02:04.290 --> 00:02:11.280
a rather heuristic
concept at the moment.

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:19.450
And I will also only give you
a very heuristic discussion.

00:02:19.450 --> 00:02:21.830
And it's possible to make it
a little bit more rigorous.

00:02:21.830 --> 00:02:27.370
But we will do it a
rather heuristic level,

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:31.340
just to give you a
feeling that there

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:38.410
is something profound going
on in quantum gravity because

00:02:38.410 --> 00:02:39.490
of black holes.

00:02:44.720 --> 00:03:03.960
So let's consider an
isolated system of mass.

00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:17.900
Say E and, say,
entropy as zero, say

00:03:17.900 --> 00:03:20.340
in asymptotic flat spacetime.

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:47.600
And then we also denote A
as the area of the smallest

00:03:47.600 --> 00:03:59.045
sphere that closes the system.

00:04:08.550 --> 00:04:13.745
And also let me
introduce-- let MA

00:04:13.745 --> 00:04:27.350
be the mass of the black hole,
of the same horizon area.

00:04:31.140 --> 00:04:33.330
Yes.

00:04:33.330 --> 00:04:42.415
Black hole with
horizon area A. OK?

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:53.490
So in GR, anything which
is sufficiently massive

00:04:53.490 --> 00:04:56.980
will eventually collapse
to form a black hole.

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:10.720
Because of that-- so we must
have E is smaller than MA,

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:13.230
So we must have E--
so whatever energy

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:16.790
you can put in this
region surrounded by area

00:05:16.790 --> 00:05:22.850
A must be smaller than
the mass of a black hole

00:05:22.850 --> 00:05:24.840
which you can put
in that region.

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:25.340
OK?

00:05:28.730 --> 00:05:30.750
Because otherwise,
if we have more mass,

00:05:30.750 --> 00:05:34.215
then it will already
be a black hole.

00:05:34.215 --> 00:05:35.549
AUDIENCE: Should that be equal?

00:05:35.549 --> 00:05:36.090
HONG LIU: Hm?

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:36.946
AUDIENCE: Should it be equal?

00:05:36.946 --> 00:05:37.760
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:38.380
Say equal.

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:50.670
So now let's suppose
E is smaller than MA.

00:05:55.880 --> 00:06:04.100
So we can now-- so suppose
E is smaller than MA

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:09.720
and now we can add
this amount of energy,

00:06:09.720 --> 00:06:21.840
say MA minus E amount of
energy, to the system.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:30.700
OK.

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:32.395
Suppose we can do
that and keep A fixed.

00:06:38.950 --> 00:06:42.490
Suppose we can do
that and keep A fixed.

00:06:42.490 --> 00:06:45.140
And then this will
reach a black hole mass.

00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:59.410
Then the final system
will have a black hole,

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:01.790
will have the
energy given by MA.

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:13.380
And that object
must be a black hole

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:15.755
because that's the black hole
with the same horizon area.

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:26.740
Because this process
also tells you

00:07:26.740 --> 00:07:32.050
that the black hole entropy
must be greater than the S0,

00:07:32.050 --> 00:07:37.650
the initial entropy of this
system, plus the S prime-- S

00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:39.635
prime is the entropy
of added energy.

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:49.690
OK.

00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:52.290
So just because of the
second law of thermodynamics,

00:07:52.290 --> 00:07:55.450
your entropy should
not decrease.

00:07:55.450 --> 00:08:02.376
So the final-- so you add this
amount of energy so to MA,

00:08:02.376 --> 00:08:07.630
so then you will precisely form
a black hole over the mass MA,

00:08:07.630 --> 00:08:11.450
and with the horizon area A.
But this black hole entropy

00:08:11.450 --> 00:08:15.550
should be greater than its
zero plus the entropy you

00:08:15.550 --> 00:08:17.550
added from the second
law of thermodynamics.

00:08:20.530 --> 00:08:29.090
So then that means your
initial entropy must be smaller

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:31.650
than the black hole entropy.

00:08:35.530 --> 00:08:41.020
Must be smaller than A
divided by 4 h bar G newton.

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:59.630
So this argument tells you
that the maximal entropy

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:16.360
inside a region bounded
by area A is given by--

00:09:28.615 --> 00:09:29.115
OK.

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:33.780
Yes?

